<p>A <b>Bayesian network</b> (also known as a <b>Bayes network</b>, <b>Baye=
s net</b>, <b>belief network</b>, or <b>decision network</b>) is a <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Probabilistic_graphical_model" class=3D"m=
w-redirect" title=3D"Probabilistic graphical model">probabilistic graphical=
 model</a> that represents a set of variables and their <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Conditional_dependence" title=3D"Conditional dependen=
ce">conditional dependencies</a> via a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Directed_acyclic_graph" title=3D"Directed acyclic graph">directed acyc=
lic graph</a> (DAG).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayesian_network#cite_note-1"><span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> While=
 it is one of several forms of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cau=
sal_notation" title=3D"Causal notation">causal notation</a>, causal network=
s are special cases of Bayesian networks. Bayesian networks are ideal for t=
aking an event that occurred and predicting the likelihood that any one of =
several possible known causes was the contributing factor.  For example, a =
Bayesian network could represent the probabilistic relationships between di=
seases and symptoms. Given symptoms, the network can be used to compute the=
 probabilities of the presence of various diseases.
</p><p>Efficient algorithms can perform <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Inference" title=3D"Inference">inference</a> and <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Machine_learning" title=3D"Machine learning">learning<=
/a> in Bayesian networks. Bayesian networks that model sequences of variabl=
es (<i>e.g.</i> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Speech_recognition=
" title=3D"Speech recognition">speech signals</a> or <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Peptide_sequence" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Peptide=
 sequence">protein sequences</a>) are called <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Dynamic_Bayesian_network" title=3D"Dynamic Bayesian network">dyn=
amic Bayesian networks</a>. Generalizations of Bayesian networks that can r=
epresent and solve decision problems under uncertainty are called <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Influence_diagram" title=3D"Influence dia=
gram">influence diagrams</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"toclimit-3"><meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc"></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Graphical_model">Graphical =
model</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-brac=
ket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DBayesi=
an_network&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D1" title=3D"Edit section: Graphi=
cal model"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</s=
pan></span></div>
<p>Formally, Bayesian networks are <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Directed_acyclic_graph" title=3D"Directed acyclic graph">directed acyclic =
graphs</a> (DAGs) whose nodes represent variables in the <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayesian_probability" title=3D"Bayesian probability"=
>Bayesian</a> sense: they may be observable quantities, <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Latent_variable" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Laten=
t variable">latent variables</a>, unknown parameters or hypotheses. Each ed=
ge represents a direct conditional dependency. Any pair of nodes that are n=
ot connected (i.e. no path connects one node to the other) represent variab=
les that are <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Conditional_independe=
nce" title=3D"Conditional independence">conditionally independent</a> of ea=
ch other. Each node is associated with a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Probability_distribution" title=3D"Probability distribution">probabi=
lity function</a> that takes, as input, a particular set of values for the =
node's <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Glossary_of_graph_theory#Di=
rected_acyclic_graphs" title=3D"Glossary of graph theory">parent</a> variab=
les, and gives (as output) the probability (or probability distribution, if=
 applicable) of the variable represented by the node. For example, if <span=
 class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math=
