<figure class=3D"mw-halign-right" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:SimpleBayesNet.svg" class=3D"mw-file-descript=
ion"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0e/=
SimpleBayesNet.svg/500px-SimpleBayesNet.svg.png" decoding=3D"async" width=
=3D"400" height=3D"226" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"575" d=
ata-file-height=3D"325"></a><figcaption>A simple Bayesian network with <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Conditional_probability_table" title=
=3D"Conditional probability table">conditional probability tables</a> </fig=
caption></figure>
<p>Suppose we want to model the dependencies between three variables: the s=
prinkler (or more appropriately, its state - whether it is on or not), the =
presence or absence of rain and whether the grass is wet or not. Observe th=
at two events can cause the grass to become wet: an active sprinkler or rai=
n. Rain has a direct effect on the use of the sprinkler (namely that when i=
t rains, the sprinkler usually is not active). This situation can be modele=
d with a Bayesian network (shown to the right). Each variable has two possi=
ble values, T (for true) and F (for false).
</p><p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joint_probability_distr=
ibution" title=3D"Joint probability distribution">joint probability functio=
n</a> is, by the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chain_rule_of_pro=
bability" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Chain rule of probability">chain r=
ule of probability</a>,
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span clas=
s=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyl=
e \Pr(G,S,R)=3D\Pr(G\mid S,R)\Pr(S\mid R)\Pr(R)}">
