<p>A back-door path is one that ends with an arrow into <i>X</i>. Sets that=
 satisfy the back-door criterion are called "sufficient" or "admissible." F=
or example, the set <i>Z</i>&nbsp;=3D&nbsp;<i>R</i> is admissible for predi=
cting the effect of <i>S</i>&nbsp;=3D&nbsp;<i>T</i> on <i>G</i>, because <i=
>R</i> <i>d</i>-separates the (only) back-door path <i>S</i>&nbsp;=E2=86=90=
&nbsp;<i>R</i>&nbsp;=E2=86=92&nbsp;<i>G</i>. However, if <i>S</i> is not ob=
served, no other set <i>d</i>-separates this path and the effect of turning=
 the sprinkler on (<i>S</i>&nbsp;=3D&nbsp;<i>T</i>) on the grass (<i>G</i>)=
 cannot be predicted from passive observations. In that case <i>P</i>(<i>G<=
/i>&nbsp;|&nbsp;do(<i>S</i>&nbsp;=3D&nbsp;<i>T</i>)) is not "identified". T=
his reflects the fact that, lacking interventional data, the observed depen=
dence between <i>S</i> and <i>G</i> is due to a causal connection or is spu=
rious
(apparent dependence arising from a common cause, <i>R</i>). (see <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Simpson%27s_paradox" title=3D"Simpson's p=
aradox">Simpson's paradox</a>)
</p><p>To determine whether a causal relation is identified from an arbitra=
ry Bayesian network with unobserved variables, one can use the three rules =
of "<i>do</i>-calculus"<sup id=3D"cite_ref-pearl2000_2-1" class=3D"referenc=
e"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayesian_network#cite_note-pear=
l2000-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-pearl-r212_5-0" class=3D"reference">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayesian_network#cite_note-pearl-r=
212-5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]=
</span></a></sup> and test whether all <i>do</i> terms can be removed from =
the expression of that relation, thus confirming that the desired quantity =
is estimable from frequency data.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-6" class=3D"reference"=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayesian_network#cite_note-6"><sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>6<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a=
></sup>
</p><p>Using a Bayesian network can save considerable amounts of memory ove=
r exhaustive probability tables, if the dependencies in the joint distribut=
ion are sparse. For example, a naive way of storing the conditional probabi=
lities of 10 two-valued variables as a table requires storage space for <sp=
an class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-ma=
th-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=
=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle 2^{10}=3D=
1024}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <msup>
          <mn>2</mn>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mn>10</mn>
          </mrow>
        </msup>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <mn>1024</mn>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle 2^{10}=3D1024=
}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/13588ba2bcf107e75098e0aac63663fa4f147e45" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.338ex; width:10.787ex; height:2.676ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle 2^=
{10}=3D1024}"></span> values. If no variable's local distribution depends o=
n more than three parent variables, the Bayesian network representation sto=
res at most <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span =
class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: non=
e;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\display=
style 10\cdot 2^{3}=3D80}">
