-align: -0.338ex; width:11.644ex; height:2.676ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle 10=
\cdot 2^{3}=3D80}"></span> values.
</p><p>One advantage of Bayesian networks is that it is intuitively easier =
for a human to understand (a sparse set of) direct dependencies and local d=
istributions than complete joint distributions.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Inference_and_learning">Inf=
erence and learning</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-ed=
itsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?=
title=3DBayesian_network&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D3" title=3D"Edit s=
ection: Inference and learning"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-edit=
section-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Bayesian networks perform three main inference tasks:
</p>
<ol><li>Inferring unobserved variables</li>
<li>Parameter learning for the probability distributions of each node in th=
e network</li>
<li>Structure learning of the graphical network</li></ol>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Inferring_unobserved_variab=
les">Inferring unobserved variables</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><spa=
n class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/w/index.php?title=3DBayesian_network&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D4"=
 title=3D"Edit section: Inferring unobserved variables"><span>edit</span></=
a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Because a Bayesian network is a complete model for its variables and the=
ir relationships, it can be used to answer probabilistic queries about them=
. For example, the network can be used to update knowledge of the state of =
a subset of variables when other variables (the <i>evidence</i> variables) =
are observed. This process of computing the <i>posterior</i> distribution o=
f variables given evidence is called probabilistic inference. The posterior=
 gives a universal <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sufficient_stat=
istic" title=3D"Sufficient statistic">sufficient statistic</a> for detectio=
n applications, when choosing values for the variable subset that minimize =
some expected loss function, for instance the probability of decision error=
. A Bayesian network can thus be considered a mechanism for automatically a=
pplying <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayes%27_theorem" title=3D=
"Bayes' theorem">Bayes' theorem</a> to complex problems.
</p><p>The most common exact inference methods are: <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Variable_elimination" title=3D"Variable elimination">vari=
able elimination</a>, which eliminates (by integration or summation) the no=
n-observed non-query variables one by one by distributing the sum over the =
product; <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Junction_tree_algorithm" =
title=3D"Junction tree algorithm">clique tree propagation</a>, which caches=
 the computation so that many variables can be queried at one time and new =
evidence can be propagated quickly; and recursive conditioning and AND/OR s=
earch, which allow for a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Space%E2%=
80%93time_tradeoff" title=3D"Space=E2=80=93time tradeoff">space=E2=80=93tim=
e tradeoff</a> and match the efficiency of variable elimination when enough=
 space is used. All of these methods have complexity that is exponential in=
 the network's <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treewidth" title=3D=
"Treewidth">treewidth</a>. The most common <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Approximate_inference" title=3D"Approximate inference">approximate=
 inference</a> algorithms are <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Impo=
rtance_sampling" title=3D"Importance sampling">importance sampling</a>, sto=
chastic <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Markov_chain_Monte_Carlo" =
title=3D"Markov chain Monte Carlo">MCMC</a> simulation, mini-bucket elimina=
tion, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Loopy_belief_propagation" cl=
ass=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Loopy belief propagation">loopy belief propaga=
tion</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Generalized_belief_propa=
gation" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Generalized belief propagation">gene=
ralized belief propagation</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Variational_Bayes" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Variational Bayes">varia=
tional methods</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Parameter_learning">Paramet=
er learning</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsectio=
n-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3D=
Bayesian_network&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D5" title=3D"Edit section: =
Parameter learning"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-brac=
ket">]</span></span></div>
<p>In order to fully specify the Bayesian network and thus fully represent =
the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joint_probability_distribution=
" title=3D"Joint probability distribution">joint probability distribution</=
a>, it is necessary to specify for each node <i>X</i> the probability distr=
ibution for <i>X</i> conditional upon <i>X</i><span class=3D"nowrap" style=
=3D"padding-left:0.1em;">'s</span> parents. The distribution of <i>X</i> co=
nditional upon its parents may have any form. It is common to work with dis=
crete or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Normal_distribution" titl=
e=3D"Normal distribution">Gaussian distributions</a> since that simplifies =
calculations. Sometimes only constraints on distribution are known; one can=
 then use the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Principle_of_maximum=
_entropy" title=3D"Principle of maximum entropy">principle of maximum entro=
py</a> to determine a single distribution, the one with the greatest <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Information_entropy" class=3D"mw-redirec=
t" title=3D"Information entropy">entropy</a> given the constraints. (Analog=
ously, in the specific context of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Dynamic_Bayesian_network" title=3D"Dynamic Bayesian network">dynamic Baye=
sian network</a>, the conditional distribution for the hidden state's tempo=
ral evolution is commonly specified to maximize the <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Entropy_rate" title=3D"Entropy rate">entropy rate</a> of =
the implied stochastic process.)
</p><p>Often these conditional distributions include parameters that are un=
known and must be estimated from data, e.g., via the <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Maximum_likelihood" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Maxim=
um likelihood">maximum likelihood</a> approach. Direct maximization of the =
likelihood (or of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Posterior_pr=
obability" title=3D"Posterior probability">posterior probability</a>) is of=
ten complex given unobserved variables. A classical approach to this proble=
m is the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Expectation-maximization_=
algorithm" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Expectation-maximization algorith=
m">expectation-maximization algorithm</a>, which alternates computing expec=
ted values of the unobserved variables conditional on observed data, with m=
aximizing the complete likelihood (or posterior) assuming that previously c=
omputed expected values are correct. Under mild regularity conditions, this=
 process converges on maximum likelihood (or maximum posterior) values for =
parameters.
</p><p>A more fully Bayesian approach to parameters is to treat them as add=
itional unobserved variables and to compute a full posterior distribution o=
ver all nodes conditional upon observed data, then to integrate out the par=
ameters. This approach can be expensive and lead to large dimension models,=
 making classical parameter-setting approaches more tractable.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Structure_learning">Structu=
re learning</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsectio=
n-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3D=
Bayesian_network&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D6" title=3D"Edit section: =
Structure learning"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-brac=
ket">]</span></span></div>
<p>In the simplest case, a Bayesian network is specified by an expert and i=
s then used to perform inference. In other applications, the task of defini=
ng the network is too complex for humans. In this case, the network structu=
re and the parameters of the local distributions must be learned from data.
</p><p>Automatically learning the graph structure of a Bayesian network (BN=
) is a challenge pursued within <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ma=
chine_learning" title=3D"Machine learning">machine learning</a>. The basic =
idea goes back to a recovery algorithm developed by Rebane and <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Judea_Pearl" title=3D"Judea Pearl">Pearl</a><s=
up id=3D"cite_ref-7" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Bayesian_network#cite_note-7"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>7=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> and rests on the distinctio=
n between the three possible patterns allowed in a 3-node DAG:
</p>
