href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayesian_network#cite_note-9"><span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>9<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></s=
up><sup id=3D"cite_ref-10" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Bayesian_network#cite_note-10"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[<=
/span>10<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>An alternative method of structural learning uses optimization-based=
 search. It requires a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scoring_fun=
ction" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Scoring function">scoring function</a=
> and a search strategy. A common scoring function is <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Posterior_probability" title=3D"Posterior probability">=
posterior probability</a> of the structure given the training data, like th=
e <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayesian_information_criterion" =
title=3D"Bayesian information criterion">BIC</a> or the BDeu. The time requ=
irement of an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Exhaustive_search" c=
lass=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Exhaustive search">exhaustive search</a> retu=
rning a structure that maximizes the score is <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Tetration" title=3D"Tetration">superexponential</a> in the numb=
er of variables. A local search strategy makes incremental changes aimed at=
 improving the score of the structure. A global search algorithm like <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Markov_chain_Monte_Carlo" title=3D"Mark=
ov chain Monte Carlo">Markov chain Monte Carlo</a> (MCMC) can avoid getting=
 trapped in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maxima_and_minima" cla=
ss=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Maxima and minima">local minima</a>. Finding a =
structure that maximizes the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mutua=
l_information" title=3D"Mutual information">mutual information</a>, typical=
ly by restricting the parent candidate set to <i>k</i> nodes<sup id=3D"cite=
_ref-11" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayes=
ian_network#cite_note-11"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>11<span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-12" class=3D"refer=
ence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayesian_network#cite_note-1=
2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>12<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</s=
pan></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-13" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayesian_network#cite_note-13"><span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">[</span>13<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> or by fi=
nding an optimal <i>k</i> on a node-per-node basis,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-14" =
class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayesian_netwo=
rk#cite_note-14"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>14<span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">]</span></a></sup> is a technique that consistently achieves high=
 scores on benchmark datasets.
</p><p>A particularly fast method for exact BN learning is to cast the prob=
lem as an optimization problem, and solve it using <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Integer_programming" title=3D"Integer programming">integer=
 programming</a>. Acyclicity constraints are added to the integer program (=
IP) during solving in the form of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Cutting-plane_method" title=3D"Cutting-plane method">cutting planes</a>.<su=
p id=3D"cite_ref-15" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Bayesian_network#cite_note-15"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>=
15<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Such method can handle pr=
oblems with up to 100 variables.
</p><p>In order to deal with problems with thousands of variables, a differ=
ent approach is necessary. One is to first sample one ordering, and then fi=
nd the optimal BN structure with respect to that ordering. This implies wor=
king on the search space of the possible orderings, which is convenient as =
it is smaller than the space of network structures. Multiple orderings are =
then sampled and evaluated. This method has been proven to be the best avai=
lable in literature when the number of variables is huge.<sup id=3D"cite_re=
f-16" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayesian=
_network#cite_note-16"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>16<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Another method consists of focusing on the sub-class of decomposable=
 models, for which the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maximum_lik=
elihood_estimate" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Maximum likelihood estimat=
e">MLE</a> have a closed form. It is then possible to discover a consistent=
 structure for hundreds of variables.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Petitjean_17-0" cl=
ass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayesian_network=
#cite_note-Petitjean-17"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>17<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Learning Bayesian networks with bounded treewidth is necessary to al=
low exact, tractable inference, since the worst-case inference complexity i=
s exponential in the treewidth k (under the exponential time hypothesis). Y=
et, as a global property of the graph, it considerably increases the diffic=
ulty of the learning process. In this context it is possible to use <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/K-tree" title=3D"K-tree">K-tree</a> for e=
ffective learning.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-18" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayesian_network#cite_note-18"><span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">[</span>18<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
