v}=3Dx_{v}\mid X_{j}=3Dx_{j}{\text{ for each }}X_{j}{\text{ that is a paren=
t of }}X_{v}\,)\end{aligned}}}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/f8f18a3121835ff1e58881ebfc0d5f8ef95b783d" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -3.171ex; width:67.549ex; height:7.509ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle {\=
begin{aligned}&amp;\operatorname {P} (X_{v}=3Dx_{v}\mid X_{i}=3Dx_{i}{\text=
{ for each }}X_{i}{\text{ that is not a descendant of }}X_{v}\,)\\[6pt]=3D{=
}&amp;P(X_{v}=3Dx_{v}\mid X_{j}=3Dx_{j}{\text{ for each }}X_{j}{\text{ that=
 is a parent of }}X_{v}\,)\end{aligned}}}"></span></dd></dl>
<p>The set of parents is a subset of the set of non-descendants because the=
 graph is <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cycle_(graph_theory)" ti=
tle=3D"Cycle (graph theory)">acyclic</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Marginal_independence_struc=
ture">Marginal independence structure</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><s=
pan class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/w/index.php?title=3DBayesian_network&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D=
13" title=3D"Edit section: Marginal independence structure"><span>edit</spa=
n></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>In general, learning a Bayesian network from data is known to be <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NP-hardness" title=3D"NP-hardness">NP-har=
d</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-21" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Bayesian_network#cite_note-21"><span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>[</span>21<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> This is due in p=
art to the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Combinatorial_explosion=
" title=3D"Combinatorial explosion">combinatorial explosion</a> of <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Directed_acyclic_graph#Combinatorial_enum=
eration" title=3D"Directed acyclic graph">enumerating DAGs</a> as the numbe=
r of variables increases. Nevertheless, insights about an underlying Bayesi=
an network can be learned from data in polynomial time by focusing on its m=
arginal independence structure:<sup id=3D"cite_ref-22" class=3D"reference">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayesian_network#cite_note-22"><sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>22<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></=
a></sup> while the conditional independence statements of a distribution mo=
deled by a Bayesian network are encoded by a DAG (according to the factoriz=
ation and Markov properties above), its marginal independence statements=E2=
=80=94the conditional independence statements in which the conditioning set=
 is empty=E2=80=94are encoded by a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Graph_(discrete_mathematics)" title=3D"Graph (discrete mathematics)">simpl=
e undirected graph</a> with special properties such as equal <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Intersection_number_(graph_theory)" title=3D"Int=
ersection number (graph theory)">intersection</a> and <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Independent_set_(graph_theory)" title=3D"Independent se=
t (graph theory)">independence numbers</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Developing_Bayesian_network=
s">Developing Bayesian networks</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span cl=
ass=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
w/index.php?title=3DBayesian_network&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D14" ti=
tle=3D"Edit section: Developing Bayesian networks"><span>edit</span></a><sp=
an class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Developing a Bayesian network often begins with creating a DAG <i>G</i> =
such that <i>X</i> satisfies the local Markov property with respect to <i>G=
</i>. Sometimes this is a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Causal_g=
raph" title=3D"Causal graph">causal</a> DAG. The conditional probability di=
stributions of each variable given its parents in <i>G</i> are assessed. In=
 many cases, in particular in the case where the variables are discrete, if=
 the joint distribution of <i>X</i> is the product of these conditional dis=
tributions, then <i>X</i> is a Bayesian network with respect to <i>G</i>.<s=
up id=3D"cite_ref-23" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Bayesian_network#cite_note-23"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span=
>23<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Markov_blanket">Markov blan=
ket</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracke=
t">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DBayesian=
_network&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D15" title=3D"Edit section: Markov =
blanket"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</spa=
n></span></div>
<p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Markov_blanket" title=3D"Ma=
rkov blanket">Markov blanket</a> of a node is the set of nodes consisting o=
f its parents, its children, and any other parents of its children. The Mar=
kov blanket renders the node independent of the rest of the network; the jo=
int distribution of the variables in the Markov blanket of a node is suffic=
ient knowledge for calculating the distribution of the node. <i>X</i> is a =
Bayesian network with respect to <i>G</i> if every node is conditionally in=
dependent of all other nodes in the network, given its <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Markov_blanket" title=3D"Markov blanket">Markov blanke=
t</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTERussellNorvig2003499_20-1" class=3D"refer=
ence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayesian_network#cite_note-F=
OOTNOTERussellNorvig2003499-20"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>20<spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"d-separation"><span class=
=3D"anchor" id=3D"d-separation"></span><i>d</i>-separation</h4><span class=
=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DBayesian_network&amp;actio=
n=3Dedit&amp;section=3D16" title=3D"Edit section: d-separation"><span>edit<=
/span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>This definition can be made more general by defining the "d"-separation =
of two nodes, where d stands for directional.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-pearl2000_=
2-3" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayesian_=
network#cite_note-pearl2000-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> We first define the "d"-separatio=
n of a trail and then we will define the "d"-separation of two nodes in ter=
ms of that.
</p><p>Let <i>P</i> be a trail from node <i>u</i> to <i>v</i>. A trail is a=
 loop-free, undirected (i.e. all edge directions are ignored) path between =
two nodes. Then <i>P</i> is said to be <i>d</i>-separated by a set of nodes=
 <i>Z</i> if any of the following conditions holds:
</p>
<ul><li><i>P</i> contains (but does not need to be entirely) a directed cha=
in, <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=3D=
"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><mat=
