<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Causal_networks">Causal net=
works</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-brac=
ket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DBayesi=
an_network&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D17" title=3D"Edit section: Causa=
l networks"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</=
span></span></div>
<p>Although Bayesian networks are often used to represent <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Causality" title=3D"Causality">causal</a> relations=
hips, this need not be the case: a directed edge from <i>u</i> to <i>v</i> =
does not require that <i>X<sub>v</sub></i> be causally dependent on <i>X<su=
b>u</sub></i>. This is demonstrated by the fact that Bayesian networks on t=
he graphs:
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span clas=
s=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyl=
e a\rightarrow b\rightarrow c\qquad {\text{and}}\qquad a\leftarrow b\leftar=
row c}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mi>a</mi>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">=E2=86=92<!-- =E2=86=92 --></mo>
        <mi>b</mi>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">=E2=86=92<!-- =E2=86=92 --></mo>
        <mi>c</mi>
        <mspace width=3D"2em"></mspace>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mtext>and</mtext>
        </mrow>
        <mspace width=3D"2em"></mspace>
        <mi>a</mi>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">=E2=86=90<!-- =E2=86=90 --></mo>
        <mi>b</mi>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">=E2=86=90<!-- =E2=86=90 --></mo>
        <mi>c</mi>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle a\rightarrow =
b\rightarrow c\qquad {\text{and}}\qquad a\leftarrow b\leftarrow c}</annotat=
ion>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/237590f76460268148ca8cc06da9f2b1181160c6" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.338ex; width:33.963ex; height:2.176ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle a\=
rightarrow b\rightarrow c\qquad {\text{and}}\qquad a\leftarrow b\leftarrow =
c}"></span></dd></dl>
<p>are equivalent: that is they impose exactly the same conditional indepen=
dence requirements.
</p><p>A causal network is a Bayesian network with the requirement that the=
 relationships be causal. The additional semantics of causal networks speci=
fy that if a node <i>X</i> is actively caused to be in a given state <i>x</=
i> (an action written as do(<i>X</i>&nbsp;=3D&nbsp;<i>x</i>)), then the pro=
bability density function changes to that of the network obtained by cuttin=
g the links from the parents of <i>X</i> to <i>X</i>, and setting <i>X</i> =
to the caused value <i>x</i>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-pearl2000_2-4" class=3D"re=
ference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayesian_network#cite_not=
e-pearl2000-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">]</span></a></sup> Using these semantics, the impact of external int=
erventions from data obtained prior to intervention can be predicted.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Inference_complexity_and_ap=
proximation_algorithms">Inference complexity and approximation algorithms</=
h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[<=
/span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DBayesian_netw=
ork&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D18" title=3D"Edit section: Inference co=
mplexity and approximation algorithms"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"=
mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>In 1990, while working at Stanford University on large bioinformatic app=
lications, Cooper proved that exact inference in Bayesian networks is <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NP-hard" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D=
"NP-hard">NP-hard</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-24" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayesian_network#cite_note-24"><span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>24<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
> This result prompted research on approximation algorithms with the aim of=
 developing a tractable approximation to probabilistic inference. In 1993, =
Paul Dagum and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Michael_Luby" title=
=3D"Michael Luby">Michael Luby</a> proved two surprising results on the com=
plexity of approximation of probabilistic inference in Bayesian networks.<s=
up id=3D"cite_ref-25" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Bayesian_network#cite_note-25"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span=
>25<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> First, they proved that =
no tractable <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Deterministic_algorit=
hm" title=3D"Deterministic algorithm">deterministic algorithm</a> can appro=
ximate probabilistic inference to within an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Absolute_error" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Absolute error">ab=
solute error</a> <i>=C9=9B</i>&nbsp;&lt;&nbsp;1/2. Second, they proved that=
 no tractable <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Randomized_algorithm=
" title=3D"Randomized algorithm">randomized algorithm</a> can approximate p=
robabilistic inference to within an absolute error <i>=C9=9B</i>&nbsp;&lt;&=
nbsp;1/2 with confidence probability greater than&nbsp;1/2.
</p><p>At about the same time, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dan=
_Roth" title=3D"Dan Roth">Roth</a> proved that exact inference in Bayesian =
networks is in fact <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sharp-P-comple=
te" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Sharp-P-complete">#P-complete</a> (and t=
hus as hard as counting the number of satisfying assignments of a <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Conjunctive_normal_form" title=3D"Conjunc=
tive normal form">conjunctive normal form</a> formula (CNF)) and that appro=
ximate inference within a factor 2<sup><i>n</i><sup>1=E2=88=92<i>=C9=9B</i>=
</sup></sup> for every <i>=C9=9B</i> &gt; 0, even for Bayesian networks wit=
h restricted architecture, is NP-hard.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-26" class=3D"refe=
rence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayesian_network#cite_note-=
26"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>26<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</=
span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-27" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayesian_network#cite_note-27"><span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">[</span>27<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In practical terms, these complexity results suggested that while Ba=
yesian networks were rich representations for AI and machine learning appli=
cations, their use in large real-world applications would need to be temper=
ed by either topological structural constraints, such as na=C3=AFve Bayes n=
etworks, or by restrictions on the conditional probabilities. The bounded v=
ariance algorithm<sup id=3D"cite_ref-28" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayesian_network#cite_note-28"><span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">[</span>28<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> devel=
oped by Dagum and Luby was the first provable fast approximation algorithm =
to efficiently approximate probabilistic inference in Bayesian networks wit=
h guarantees on the error approximation. This powerful algorithm required t=
he minor restriction on the conditional probabilities of the Bayesian netwo=
rk to be bounded away from zero and one by <span class=3D"mwe-math-element =
mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mat=
hml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Ma=
