<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Software">Software</h2><spa=
n class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DBayesian_network&amp=
;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D19" title=3D"Edit section: Software"><span>edi=
t</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Notable software for Bayesian networks include:
</p>
<ul><li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/OpenBUGS" title=3D"OpenBUG=
S">OpenBUGS</a> =E2=80=93 Open-source development of WinBUGS.</li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SPSS_Modeler" title=3D"SPSS Mo=
deler">SPSS Modeler</a> =E2=80=93 Commercial software that includes an impl=
ementation for Bayesian networks.</li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stan_(software)" title=3D"Stan=
 (software)">Stan (software)</a> =E2=80=93 Stan is an open-source package f=
or obtaining Bayesian inference using the No-U-Turn sampler (NUTS),<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-29" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Bayesian_network#cite_note-29"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>29<s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> a variant of Hamiltonian Mont=
e Carlo.</li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WinBUGS" title=3D"WinBUGS">Win=
BUGS</a> =E2=80=93 One of the first computational implementations of MCMC s=
amplers. No longer maintained.</li></ul>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"History">History</h2><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DBayesian_network&amp;a=
ction=3Dedit&amp;section=3D20" title=3D"Edit section: History"><span>edit</=
span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The term Bayesian network was coined by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Judea_Pearl" title=3D"Judea Pearl">Judea Pearl</a> in 1985 to emph=
asize:<sup id=3D"cite_ref-30" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Bayesian_network#cite_note-30"><span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>[</span>30<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<ul><li>the often subjective nature of the input information</li>
<li>the reliance on Bayes' conditioning as the basis for updating informati=
on</li>
<li>the distinction between causal and evidential modes of reasoning<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-31" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Bayesian_network#cite_note-31"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>31<s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li></ul>
<p>In the late 1980s Pearl's <i>Probabilistic Reasoning in Intelligent Syst=
ems</i><sup id=3D"cite_ref-32" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Bayesian_network#cite_note-32"><span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">[</span>32<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> and <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Richard_E._Neapolitan" class=3D"mw-redirect" =
title=3D"Richard E. Neapolitan">Neapolitan</a>'s <i>Probabilistic Reasoning=
 in Expert Systems</i><sup id=3D"cite_ref-33" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayesian_network#cite_note-33"><span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>33<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
> summarized their properties and established them as a field of study.
</p>
